## Section 8: Research Agent — Live Web Crawl

### 8.1 What Tavily Is and Why We Use It

Tavily is an API (Application Programming Interface — a service you call over the internet) built specifically for AI agents that need to search and retrieve information from the web. Unlike a regular search engine that returns links, Tavily returns the actual content of relevant articles — cleaned, parsed, and ready to process. It handles Indian news sources, handles queries in English, and returns results fast enough for near-real-time use.

Why not just use Google? Google's search API is heavily restricted and expensive. Tavily is purpose-built for this use case, has a generous free tier suitable for a hackathon, and returns content rather than just links — which is what we need since we want to feed article text into FinBERT.

### 8.2 Two-Phase Crawl Architecture

**Phase 1 — Background Deep Crawl (runs when case is created, asynchronously)**
This is the heavy research work. It runs in the background while documents are being uploaded and processed. It does not block anything.

Queries run (15–20 total, templated):
- "{company_name} fraud scam controversy India"
- "{promoter_name} court case DRT NCLT India"
- "{company_name} insolvency default NPA bank"
- "{company_name} credit rating downgrade"
- "{sector} RBI regulation circular 2025"
- "{sector} India outlook headwinds challenges"
- "{promoter_name} related party transaction controversy"
- "{company_name} auditor resignation qualification"
- And 8–10 more covering variations of the above

Each result is fetched (full article text), parsed, and run through FinBERT for risk severity scoring. Results are cached with timestamp, source URL, query that found them, and the FinBERT risk category and severity assigned.

**Phase 2 — Live Refresh (runs during demo, takes 5–8 seconds)**
A narrow, targeted live crawl of 3–5 queries focused on the most recent period. This is what the judge sees happening in real time. Results are appended to the cached research and any new risk signals are highlighted as "newly discovered."

The UI shows a live query log during this phase — judges can watch the queries run and see results populate.

### 8.3 Conflict Resolution

If a live crawl result contradicts cached research — for example, a promoter was acquitted of a case that was flagged as active litigation in the background crawl — the system does not silently overwrite. It surfaces the contradiction as an explicit flag: "Conflicting information found — cached research flagged active DRT case, new result suggests case dismissed. Manual verification recommended." The credit officer must resolve this with a note before the CAM is finalized.

### 8.4 Research Agent Log

The UI displays a complete, transparent log of every query run, every source found, the FinBERT severity score assigned to each, and which Five C and signal it fed into. This directly satisfies the "research depth" evaluation criterion — judges can verify that the system found information not present in the uploaded documents.

